\subsection{Cover-totality source-object identification (iter-031)}

Step 3 (the cover-totality identification on cohomology) is more substantive than the iter-030 sketch admitted. Three obstructions surface on the iter-031 plan-agent re-probe:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Universe mismatch}: $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$ lives in $\Type\,(u+1)$ but $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X$ lives in $\Type\,u$ — the two declarations are at different universes by design (iter-009 / iter-014). A direct $\equiv_{\Module k}$ between them does not typecheck without a universe lift.
  \item \textbf{Mathlib's analog is an explicit TODO}: \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/Basic.lean} (lines 31--34) lists ``if $U$ is a terminal object of $C$, define an isomorphism $(F.\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\op U) \equiv_+ \mathtt{Sheaf.H}\,F\,n$'' as a TODO. We must build it ourselves.
  \item \textbf{The proof body is multi-step}: the natural construction goes (a) $\yoneda(\top) \cong \mathtt{const}\,\PUnit$ (terminal-collapse), (b) whisker right with $\mathtt{ModuleCat.free}\,k$ to get $\mathtt{const}\,(\mathtt{free}\,k\,\PUnit)$, (c) $(\mathtt{free}\,k).\mathrm{obj}\,\PUnit \cong \ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k$ via $\mathtt{Finsupp.LinearEquiv.finsuppUnique}$, (d) sheafify (using $\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,D = \mathtt{Functor.const}\,C^{\op} \circ \mathtt{presheafToSheaf}\,J\,D$).
\end{enumerate}

Iter-031 plan-agent decomposition decision: rather than tackle the full $\equiv_{\Module k}$ on cohomology (which conflates the source-iso construction, Ext-transport, and universe handling), iter-031 closes \emph{only} the source-object iso at the sheaf level. The Ext-transport step plus universe handling are deferred to iter-032+.

\begin{definition}[Cover-totality source-object identification, iter-031]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_top_sourceIso}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_top_sourceIso}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category with morphism universe $u$, $J : \GrothendieckTopology\,C$, $T : C$ a terminal object (witnessed by $h_T : \mathtt{IsTerminal}\,T$), and assume $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\Type\,u)$ and $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$. There is a natural isomorphism in $\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$:
  \[
    (\presheafToSheaf\,J\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,
        ((\yoneda \circ (\Functor.\mathtt{whiskeringRight}\,\_\,\_\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathtt{free}\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,T)
      \;\cong\;
      (\constantSheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k).
  \]
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \leanok
  Compose three Mathlib pieces, using the identity $\constantSheaf\,J\,D = \Functor.\mathtt{const}\,C^{\op} \circ \presheafToSheaf\,J\,D$ (\texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/ConstantSheaf.lean}, line 65):
  \begin{enumerate}
    \item $\yoneda.\mathrm{obj}\,T \cong (\Functor.\mathtt{const}\,C^{\op}).\mathrm{obj}\,\PUnit$ — the terminal-collapse: at object $X^{\op}$ both presheaves evaluate to a one-element type, with the iso supplied component-wise via $\mathtt{IsTerminal.from}$ for the inverse and $\mathtt{IsTerminal.hom\_ext}$ for the section identity.
    \item Whisker right with $(\Functor.\mathtt{whiskeringRight}\,\_\,\_\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathtt{free}\,k)$, then apply $\Functor.\mathtt{constComp}$ to obtain $((\Functor.\mathtt{const}\,C^{\op}).\mathrm{obj}\,\PUnit) \circ \ModuleCat.\mathtt{free}\,k = (\Functor.\mathtt{const}\,C^{\op}).\mathrm{obj}\,((\ModuleCat.\mathtt{free}\,k).\mathrm{obj}\,\PUnit)$ as an iso.
    \item Apply $(\Functor.\mathtt{const}\,C^{\op}).\mathtt{mapIso}$ to the linear-equivalence-derived iso $(\ModuleCat.\mathtt{free}\,k).\mathrm{obj}\,\PUnit \cong \ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k$ (via $\mathtt{Finsupp.LinearEquiv.finsuppUnique}\,k\,k\,\PUnit$ followed by $\mathtt{LinearEquiv.toModuleIso}$).
  \end{enumerate}
  Apply $(\presheafToSheaf\,J\,\_).\mathtt{mapIso}$ to the composed presheaf-level iso to land in $\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$; the right-hand side then unfolds via the $\constantSheaf$ identity above.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Use in Serre finiteness}

The iter-029 lemmas materialise Step 1 (the abstract LES) and Step 2 (the corner-identification simp lemmas) of the iter-028 Serre-finiteness sketch (Section~\ref{sec:scheme_affineCoverMVSquare}); iter-030 materialised Step 2.5 (the toModuleKSheaf specialisation, a routine binding so downstream code paths can reference the LES on the structure sheaf of a curve directly); iter-031 (this iteration) materialises the \emph{source-object} half of Step 3 (the cover-totality identification, leaving the Ext-transport step plus universe handling to iter-032+). The remaining work — Step 3-rest (the LinearEquiv on cohomology $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,T \equiv_{\Module k} \HModule\,k\,F\,n$ for terminal $T$, with universe lift), Step 4 (affine vanishing $H^{>0}(\Spec A, \mathcal F) = 0$, possibly multi-iteration depending on Mathlib state), and Step 5 (finiteness of each $H^0$ piece, hence of $H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$) — is iter-032+.

